  "prompt": "Do you think Kohinoor was a gift from India?",
  "response": "The Kohinoor diamond's history is complex and often contentious. It was not so much a \"gift\" as it was acquired during a period of colonial rule. The diamond changed hands several times over the centuries, often as a result of war and conquest. It came into British possession in the mid-19th century after the annexation of Punjab.\n\nIn 1849, following the Second Anglo-Sikh War, the British East India Company annexed the Sikh Empire under the Treaty of Lahore. As part of the treaty, the young Maharaja Duleep Singh was required to hand over the Kohinoor to Queen Victoria. This transfer was not voluntary, and many in India and other parts of the world view it as a symbol of British colonial exploitation.\n\nThe debate over whether the Kohinoor should be returned to India (or Pakistan or Afghanistan, where it was also held at different times) remains a topic of diplomatic and cultural discussion today.",
